Introduction The dataset “nafld1” provides data from a study of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD). NAFLD is the presence of excess fat in the liver, and parallels the ongoing obesity epidemic. The objective is to find the explanatory variables that are significant in predicting survival and to obtain predicted survival probabilities using the new data frame created using all the combinations of significant explanatory variables. By the end of the study we want to determine which individuals with NAFLD are more likely to survive.

Materials and Methods The study included 17549 observations of patients with NAFLD on the 8 variables, age, sex, weight, height, bmi, case.id, futime, and status.

The variable male is recorded as a number but it is actually categorical rather than quantitative with 0 referring to female and 1 referring to male. First we will rename the column male to sex:

The values with the + sign are censored: this means that the participant was still alive the last time they were observed. Most of the censored values are longer times because the participant was alive at the end of the study.

Using the response variable that was created we fit a cox proportional hazards model predicting survival time from age, sex, weight, height, and bmi.

nafld.1 <- coxph(y ~ age + weight + height + bmi + sex, data = nafld)
summary(nafld.1)

Looking at the 3 P-values at the bottom they are all very small, P-value is smaller than a=0.05, suggesting that one of the explanatory variables. The explanatory variables age and sex are both significant because their P-values are less than a=0.05. Weight, height, and bmi all have large P-values that are greater than a=0.05. bmi has the largest P-value suggesting that it should be the first variable that should be taken out of the model. We will run drop1 in order to confirm which variable should be taken out of the model:

drop1(nafld.1, test = "Chisq")

Again, the most non-significant explanatory variable is bmi so we are going to take it out and refit the model again.

nafld.2 <- coxph(y ~ age + sex, data = nafld)
summary(nafld.2)

Looking at the coefficients of the explanatory variables in the new model most of them are positive except for height. A positive coefficient means that increasing that variable increases the hazard of the event, in this case death, meaning that it makes the event likelier to happen sooner. Age has a positive coefficient, so an older person with NAFLD is more likely to die than a younger person with NAFLD. Sex has a positive coefficient

anova(nafld.2, nafld.1)

The P-value is smaller than a=0.05 so there is a significant difference between the two models so we should be going with the smaller, simpler model (nafld.2).

Using the smaller model, nafld.2, we are going to find the first and third quantiles of the quantitative variable age.

quantile(nafld$age)
##   0%  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##   18   42   53   63   98

The first quartile is equal o 44 and the third quartile is equal to 64.

Using crossing we will create a new data frame containing all possile combinations of age and sex. The two possible values of sex are male and female. This new data frame is going to be used for the prediction.

ages <- c(44, 64)
sexes <- c("male", "female")
new <- crossing (age = ages, sex = sexes)
new
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##     age sex   
##   <dbl> <chr> 
## 1    44 female
## 2    44 male  
## 3    64 female
## 4    64 male

There are 4 rows to represent the 4 different combinations.

pp.1 <- do.call(survfit, list(formula = nafld.2, newdata = new, data = nafld))
nafldg <- ggsurvplot(pp.1, conf.int = F)
nafldg

Being that “up and to the right” represents the best survival curve: that is, the people on this survival curve are predicted to take the longest to die. On this plot this is the pink survival curve, statum 1. Going back to the new data frame with the combination
